\begin{abstract}
AI assistants increasingly help researchers discuss hypotheses,
inspect logs, and interpret experimental results, but their outputs
rarely become reliable scientific state. We propose a pluggable
negative knowledge memory layer for AutoResearch systems: when an AI
system produces a hypothesis, experimental result, plan revision, or
memory update, this layer requires the candidate state update to bind
claims to evidence, failure type, uncertainty, recommended action, and
review status. The technical focus is not autonomous discovery, but
state mutation control: every proposed finding must cite project-local
evidence, and failed or inconclusive routes must be represented
explicitly rather than collapsed into success-oriented summaries. We
introduce a bounded failure schema with six fields---failure layer,
scope, degree, reproducibility, recommended action, and risk---and
show how it can be embedded in memory updates, plan revision, report
writing, and multi-agent communication. We evaluate the layer on a
public scientific coding benchmark and a partial-differential-equation
numerical-methods case study, measuring whether structured negative
knowledge predicts failure repairability, reduces memory cost in
multi-round retry, and supports multi-agent sharing. Our goal is a
reproducible human-audited mechanism that turns agent-local failures
into shared negative knowledge for AI-assisted research.
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:intro}
{\color{orange}
AutoResearch systems aim to automate or semi-automate parts of the
scientific research process---literature retrieval, hypothesis
generation, experiment planning and execution, result analysis,
review, and writing
\citep{lu2024aiscientist,schmidgall2025agentlab,gottweis2025aicoscientist,
chen2024scienceagentbench,gu2024blade}. These systems treat research
as an iterative pipeline that uses prior scientific artifacts and
experimental feedback to produce new candidate findings.
}

{\color{orange}
However, the dominant orientation of AutoResearch remains
success-seeking. Existing workflows primarily ask how prior successful
knowledge can be retrieved, recombined, and extended into new
successful results; failures appear as local debugging signals but
rarely become durable research objects. This leaves out a second form
of scientific memory: \emph{negative knowledge}---failed hypotheses,
non-working methods, abandoned experimental routes, rejected
interpretations, boundary conditions, and unresolved anomalies. It is
not the mere absence of success: it prevents researchers and agents
from repeatedly exploring the same dead ends, clarifies the limits of
current claims, and exposes parts of the research space where further
inquiry is still needed.
}

{\color{orange}
The focus on positive knowledge alone reflects a historical,
long-standing publication bias, extensively discussed in the
philosophy and sociology of science
\citep{popper1959logic,kuhn1962structure,lakatos1970falsification,
rosenthal1979filedrawer,ioannidis2005false}. For human scholars,
emphasising failed routes carries low individual reward; failed work
therefore survives primarily as informal tacit knowledge circulated
within laboratories and expert communities
\citep{polanyi1966tacit,collins2010tacit}. The prevailing scientific
paradigm offers no structural reward for human scholars to spend
resources producing, preserving, or sharing negative knowledge. The
cost is collective inefficiency: a failed route has little value as
an individual success claim, yet substantial value for the research
community at large. Collective reciprocity and individual
self-interest are in direct tension at this point.
}

{\color{orange}
In multi-agent AutoResearch, an agent does not need publication
credit; it has no human-style self-interest, which directly changes
the underlying game-theoretic relation. An agent can therefore be
assigned a different epistemic role---a system-level subject that
spends real resources to generate, preserve, and maintain negative
knowledge as a shared asset. For human scholars, sustained
low-reward labor of this kind is nearly impossible. Even for LLMs
and other large-scale systems, recording and storing negative
knowledge is difficult, because the system rarely receives a reward
signal for the wide variety of unsuccessful situations it
encounters. At the same time, a research system rewarded only for
producing coherent positive narratives may learn to imitate the
human success economy: smoothing over uncertainty, overstating
progress, or packaging failed explorations as persuasive narratives.
Such false progress can be more dangerous than ordinary stagnation:
missing a possible discovery usually only delays research, but
advancing on the basis of false discoveries can misdirect an entire
research line into long-term failure.
}

{\color{orange}
We therefore propose a minimal framework for maintaining negative
knowledge: agents create, maintain, and inspect negative knowledge
inline with their AutoResearch workflow, and humans can intervene to
revise it at any point. This paper studies a small but operational
first step---a project-level AutoResearch setting in which a few AI
agents and human researchers jointly maintain reviewable negative
knowledge. The broader vision is that the scientific community itself
can be understood as the largest AutoResearch system: once AI agents
remove researcher productivity as a socially scarce resource,
negative knowledge can become maintainable and shareable public
epistemic infrastructure.
}

{\color{orange}
This paper makes three contributions. First, we define an
architecture-agnostic negative knowledge memory layer for
human-audited agent-assisted research. Second, we introduce a bounded
failure schema that turns failed routes into structured research
objects and inter-agent communication resources. Third, we report a
pilot evaluation on a scientific coding benchmark and a PDE
numerical-methods case study, measuring whether structured negative
knowledge predicts failure repairability, reduces memory cost in
multi-round retry, and supports multi-agent sharing.
}

\section{Method: Negative Knowledge Memory Layer}
\label{sec:workflow}

% --- BEGIN: old Section 2 contents, commented out 2026-05-13 for rewrite ---
% (kept in source so we can compare against the new version)
\iffalse
Existing AutoResearch systems can be abstracted as a cyclic pipeline:
a research goal triggers literature or knowledge retrieval; the system
generates hypotheses or research ideas; a planner designs experiments,
proof attempts, simulations, or analyses; an executor runs code,
tools, simulations, experiments, or proof search; analysis and
debugging modules interpret results; a memory module updates long-term
research state; and a writer or reviewer module produces reports,
paper drafts, or the next plan. Systems differ in the number of
agents, tools, and domains, but they all face the same question: which
agent outputs should enter persistent research state?

Our method is a negative knowledge memory layer attached at this state
mutation boundary. It does not replace the hypothesis generator,
experiment runner, theorem prover, or paper writer. Instead, before
those modules write to long-term memory, revise a plan, or generate a
report, the layer records the attempted epistemic move, the
observation, the evidence, the boundary of the failure, and the
recommended next action. Concretely, it exposes three hooks:

\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Pre-action retrieval}: retrieve similar negative
  knowledge before proposing a new plan, reducing repeated
  exploration.
  \item \textbf{Post-action recording}: after experiments,
  simulations, proof attempts, or analyses, record negative, partial,
  and inconclusive outcomes.
  \item \textbf{Pre-report validation}: before writing reports or
  papers, check whether failed or inconclusive evidence is being
  framed as positive progress.
\end{itemize}

In multi-agent AutoResearch systems, failures are often local to the
agent that encountered them. A coder agent may observe an
implementation failure; an experiment agent may observe a
regime-bound instability; a reviewer agent may reject an overclaim;
and a planner agent may abandon a route because of cost. Without a
shared failure representation, these local observations do not
reliably become system-level memory. Agent A may fail on a route that
Agent B later repeats; Agent C may rewrite negative evidence as
partial success; Agent D may propose the same experiment in the next
planning round.

Bounded failure records provide a communication protocol for sharing
negative knowledge across agents. The protocol does not require all
agents to use the same internal memory. It only requires state updates
to share a minimal set of fields: attempted target, observed evidence,
failure layer, scope, degree, reproducibility, recommended action,
risk, and review status. Thus the record is not only a human-facing
audit trail. It is also a multi-agent coordination layer that helps
agents distinguish implementation bugs, method limitations,
regime-specific failures, and hypothesis-level contradictions.

A central design choice is to represent failure explicitly. Scientific
errors are not binary. A failed run may indicate an implementation
bug, a measurement artifact, a method limitation, a contradicted
hypothesis, an invalid inference, or merely an over-strong
communication of a partial result. Collapsing these cases into a
single \texttt{failed} status loses the information that makes negative
knowledge reusable.
We call the resulting object a \emph{bounded failure record}: a
structured record of what claim or hypothesis was tested, under which
conditions, what failed, what evidence supports that diagnosis, what
alternative explanations remain, and how the failure should affect
future work. We represent bounded failures using six core fields:

\begin{table}[tb]
\centering
\caption{Six fields in the bounded failure schema.}
\label{tab:failure-schema}
\begin{tabular}{ll}
\toprule
Field & Example values \\
\midrule
Layer & implementation, data, method, hypothesis \\
Scope & local, regime-bound, general, unknown \\
Degree & contradicted, partial, inconclusive, unstable \\
Reproducibility & observed once, same setup, independent \\
Action & retry, revise, change method, narrow, abandon \\
Risk & omission, drift, false progress, tail-risk hallucination \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

Each candidate state update must cite project-local evidence and may be
accepted, rejected, or revised before it changes persistent research
state. Failure-specific validation is intentionally simple: negative or
inconclusive findings must include a failure layer, scope, and degree;
an implementation failure cannot directly become a hypothesis-level
refutation; and inconclusive evidence cannot create a strong support
edge. These rules do not determine scientific truth. They prevent
unsupported state changes and force failed, partial, or inconclusive
evidence to remain bounded.

The Research Graph is our minimal reference substrate for maintaining
this structure. It keeps four basic node types---questions,
experiments, findings, and decisions---and edges that encode how
evidence changes the project state. The graph is not the contribution
by itself: the bounded failure record can also be stored as notebook
metadata, workflow provenance, an experiment-tracker record, an agent
memory entry, or a benchmark trace. The graph simply provides the
smallest structured form in which accepted findings, rejected updates,
open uncertainties, and negative knowledge can coexist.
\fi
