% --- NEW Section 2 (rewrite begun 2026-05-13) ---
% Paragraph 1 of 6: introduce method + define negative knowledge + preview producer/consumer workflow
We introduce a \emph{negative knowledge memory layer}, a thin layer
that sits between attempts and the project's long-term
research state and turns each failed attempt into a reusable record
rather than a transient log entry. A piece of \emph{negative
knowledge} is a bounded structured summary of one attempt that
captures what was tried, what failed, where in the research process
the failure sits, and what the next attempt should do differently.
To construct and use such records, our method combines a bounded
record schema with an autonomous agentic workflow that is portable
across agent architectures. The schema prescribes what each record
must contain. The workflow uses
multiple agents to organize the information flowing through
autonomous research: a \emph{producer} agent writes one record from
the artifacts of a finished attempt into a shared \emph{bank}, and a
\emph{consumer} agent reads from that bank and marks which records
it adopts and which it rejects before proposing its next experiment.

% Paragraph 2 of 6: schema design rationale + three properties + benefits + evaluation pointer
The negative knowledge schema is designed so that each record can
serve both of its roles in the workflow: a producer writes the record
from a finished attempt's artifacts, and a downstream consumer reads
it in full and acts on it without going back to raw logs. To
support both roles, the schema has three properties:
(1) \emph{Attempt-level.} Each record covers a single attempt, so the
unit of memory is tied to that attempt rather than to the session or
agent that produced it.
(2) \emph{Bounded.} Each record has fixed upper limits on length and
structure, which lets the full bank be passed to a downstream agent
inline rather than retrieved on demand.
(3) \emph{Typed.} The main fields take values from closed
enumerations, so the producer commits to a specific classification of
the failure rather than describing it in vague prose.
These properties make a record self-contained enough to travel
between agents and tasks and easy for a human reviewer to audit,
which is what allows a project to accumulate negative knowledge over
time rather than rebuild it for each attempt. A typical record
describes one attempt, for instance one that tried an explicit
time-stepping scheme on a stiff PDE, labels the failure with a small
set of closed categories, and remains short enough to be read in
full by the next agent. We provide a detailed example of the schema
in Section~\ref{sec:evaluation}.

% Paragraph 3 of 6: workflow transition + producer role + rationale + handoff
We now introduce how to use the negative knowledge schema as a layer
for agents. We propose the following multi-agent workflow: a producer
agent writes one record into the bank after every finished attempt,
and a consumer agent reads from the bank before every new attempt
begins.
The \textbf{producer} is a separate agent from the one that ran the
attempt; once that attempt finishes, the producer combines the
artifacts the attempt left behind (e.g., the executed code, its
execution output, any evaluator output, and the attempt's reasoning
notes) into one schema-conforming record. The reason for this
separation is that an agent that has just finished an unsuccessful
attempt carries enough context to pull its own description of the
failure toward what almost worked, while a producer that sees only
the frozen artifacts has no such bias. For instance, if an attempt
at a stiff PDE ran an explicit Runge-Kutta scheme and overflowed
into NaN, the producer might write a record that names the chosen
scheme, classifies the failure as method-level due to numerical
instability, and recommends a semi-implicit alternative for related
problems. As attempts proceed, the bank accumulates these
third-party records, forming the project's durable
memory of failed attempts that every downstream consumer agent can
draw on.

% Paragraph 4 of 6: consumer role + grounding requirement + concrete example + handoff
The \textbf{consumer} then reads from the bank before launching its
attempt, using the records it finds there to plan the experiment.
It reads under an explicit grounding requirement: each record must
be marked as adopted or rejected, with a justification tying the
decision to the specific failure mode the record describes. This
turns documented failures into active constraints on the next
attempt. For instance, when planning a numerical solve on a coupled
partial differential equation, a consumer may find a bank record
warning that an explicit time-stepping scheme blows up on the stiff
part of the equation, and must then either commit to a different
scheme or justify why the warning does not apply in the current
setting, so that the next attempt avoids a failure mode the project
has already documented. The consumer's output is the next attempt
itself, whose artifacts feed the producer pass that follows and add
a new record to the bank, closing the workflow loop.

% Paragraph 5 of 5: synthesis (input/method/agents/output) + purpose + bridge to evaluation
Overall, the negative knowledge layer takes the artifacts of each
finished attempt as input, uses the producer to compress them into
one schema-conforming record in the bank, and uses the consumer to
read those records when planning the next attempt. The intended
effect is that a research project pays the cost of a failed route
only once: subsequent attempts can focus on routes not yet ruled
out, the project's negative knowledge accumulates rather than being
rediscovered, and research outcomes improve over the long run. We evaluate this design across
two scientific computing settings: a same-task setting, in which a
record from one attempt informs a retry of the same task, and a
cross-task setting, in which a bank of records from prior tasks
informs an attempt on a new task.

\section{Benchmark Evaluation: Same-task Negative-Knowledge Retry}\label{sec:evaluation}
This section evaluates the negative knowledge layer in a controlled same-task retry setting on a standard scientific-coding benchmark. The goal is to isolate whether a structured negative-knowledge record, written from the artifacts of a failed attempt, can help an agent repair the same task when it has no access to the previous conversation or memory condition. We compare negative knowledge retry against direct retry and self debug baselines using previous error messages, and find that structured negative knowledge provides useful repair information while substantially reducing the memory shown to the next attempt.

