\section{Case Study: Negative Knowledge in a Multi-Agent Research Loop}
\label{sec:case-study}

We test bounded negative knowledge in a real research workflow,
not on a benchmark. A multi-agent AutoResearch team is tasked
with exploring the physics of a multi-field nonlinear PDE: the
Burgers-swept-KdV (BKdV) coupled system of Holm et~al.\ (2025).
This setting differs from benchmark evaluation in three concrete
ways: (i)~there is no fixed target, only an open phenomenology
to characterise; (ii)~there is no closed-form reference solution;
(iii)~success is whether the team produces an interesting and
defensible physical observation, not whether an output matches a
gold answer. Failures correspondingly take richer forms than in a
benchmark: numerical blow-up, runs that finish but miss the
phenomenon, and runs that are numerically valid but
scientifically uninformative. The case study tests whether
structured negative knowledge helps the team navigate this
richer failure space.

The BKdV system couples a Burgers-like current $u$ to a KdV-like
wave $v$,
\begin{align*}
  u_t + 3 u u_x &= -\partial_x\!\left(3 v^2 + \gamma v_{xx}\right), \\
  v_t + 6 v v_x + \gamma v_{xxx} &= -\partial_x(u v).
\end{align*}
The reduction $m := u - v^2/2 = 0$ collapses to a Gardner equation
in $v$; the three limits (Burgers, KdV, Gardner) are known while
the coupled regime is partially open. The case study runs in two
stages: \textbf{Stage~1} produces a structured knowledge bank
from stress tests on the component PDEs; \textbf{Stage~2} uses
that bank to study three coupled-system sub-questions under
three knowledge conditions. Per-task specifications, eval
thresholds, the stress-test catalogue, and the bank inventory are
in \cref{appendix:bkdv-setup,appendix:bkdv-bank}.

\subsection{Stage~1: Knowledge production via forced basic methods}
\label{sec:pde-stage1}

\paragraph{Why forced basic methods.} Each source agent is
forced to use a basic numerical scheme and is explicitly
forbidden from substituting more sophisticated alternatives,
because \emph{advanced methods already silently absorb the
negative knowledge we want to measure}. A limiter exists because
central differences develop Gibbs oscillations at shocks; IMEX
exists because explicit time stepping is unstable on third-order
dispersion; HLL exists because forward-Euler central schemes
drive shallow-water height negative. Letting an agent reach for
MUSCL or IMEX from the start lets it execute a recipe rather
than reason about why simpler choices fail, and the negative
knowledge becomes invisible to the experiment. The constraint
also enforces \emph{fault isolation}: when an attempt fails we
want to know which numerical layer is responsible, which is
impossible if many advanced components are stacked from the
start---in a holistic-confounding sense, too many components
make every failure compatible with too many causes, and the
experiment loses attributable signal. Forcing the basic method
externalises the failure signal at the layer it actually occurs.
This also mirrors how real research proceeds: try basic, observe
failure, only then escalate.

\paragraph{Stress tests and curation.}
Fourteen forced-method stress tests cover Burgers shock, KdV
soliton, shallow-water dam break, and Gardner soliton, plus
edge parameter regimes (very short or long $T$, very small or
large IC amplitude, dry-bed initial condition). Outcomes are
classified into three failure types using the same six-field
schema: \textbf{F1}~numerical (NaN, blow-up, positivity loss),
\textbf{F2}~result (the run finishes but the expected
phenomenon is absent or wrong), and \textbf{F3}~scientific-value
(numerically valid but uninformative for the research goal).
F3 cannot arise on a benchmark with a fixed target; it is
specific to open research and is the failure type the case study
most distinctively exercises. A curator sub-agent reads all
stress-test artefacts plus three prior BKdV pilots and writes a
structured bank; a parent audit confirms that all 30 entries
cite real evidence files (30/30 pass).

\begin{table}[tb]
\centering
\caption{Stage~1 bank composition: 30 entries, 30/30 with
audited evidence references.}
\label{tab:bkdv-bank}
\begin{tabular}{lrrr}
\toprule
Domain & Positive & Negative & Total \\
\midrule
Burgers       & 2 &  3 &  5 \\
KdV           & 4 &  3 &  7 \\
Shallow water & 2 &  3 &  5 \\
Gardner       & 2 &  7 &  9 \\
General (cross-domain) & 0 &  4 &  4 \\
\midrule
Total         & 10 & 20 & 30 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

Cross-domain general entries record principles that emerge only
when multiple stress tests are read together: ``finiteness is
not accuracy'' (multiple runs return finite output with wrong
amplitude or spurious peaks), ``central differences on
hyperbolic conservation laws fail regardless of equation'', and
``mass conservation alone is insufficient as a correctness
diagnostic for soliton-bearing systems''.

\subsection{Stage~2: Three sub-questions, three conditions}
\label{sec:pde-stage2}

\paragraph{Sub-questions.} The team studies three open
phenomenology questions on the coupled system:
\textbf{T-A} soliton stability near the $m=0$ manifold;
\textbf{T-B} whether a Gaussian wave packet decomposes into a
soliton train under coupled dynamics;
\textbf{T-C} whether a soliton survives crossing a Burgers bore
with a detectable speed or amplitude shift. None has a
closed-form reference; success is judged by deterministic
phenomenon checks (no LLM judge): mass-drift bounds, peak count
and amplitude conditions, and boundedness. Initial conditions are
calibrated to the edge where naive choices fail, so a single
round cannot trivially solve the sub-question and the conditions
below remain distinguishable.

\paragraph{Three conditions.} Each sub-question is studied under
three conditions. \textbf{NoKB}: no bank.
\textbf{PosOnly}: Stage~1's ten positive entries.
\textbf{PosNeg}: the full 30-entry bank (10 positive plus 20
negative). PosOnly versus PosNeg isolates the marginal
contribution of \emph{negative} knowledge over a successes-only
baseline; NoKB versus PosOnly isolates the contribution of any
structured knowledge. Each (sub-question, condition) cell allows
up to three internal rounds with a \texttt{finding\_record}
propagated across rounds within the cell but not across cells,
keeping the only across-cell distinction the Stage~1 bank.
Total budget $3 \times 3 \times 3 = 27$ agent calls with early
stop on a useful phenomenon.

\paragraph{Metrics.} Per cell we record numerical validity,
conservation drift, whether the phenomenon check passes, total
token cost, and the number of bank entries the agent's
\texttt{reasoning.md} explicitly cites. The headline question is
whether PosNeg reaches a useful phenomenon in fewer rounds and at
lower token cost than NoKB or PosOnly. The citation count
provides an audit: did the agent actually consult the bank, or
was the bank merely attached without effect?

\paragraph{Outcomes.} Of $3\times 3 = 9$ cells, only the two
PosNeg cells T-A and T-C produce a useful phenomenon, and both
do so at the first round; PosNeg's third cell T-B fails through
all three rounds, as do every NoKB and PosOnly cell.
\Cref{tab:bkdv-main} summarises the trajectories.

\begin{table}[tb]
\centering
\caption{Stage~2 outcomes over up to three rounds per
(sub-task, condition) cell. \xmark{} marks a failed round;
\cmark{}~r1 marks a cell that succeeded at round~1 and
stopped early.}
\label{tab:bkdv-main}
\begin{tabular}{l ccc}
\toprule
Sub-task & NoKB & PosOnly & PosNeg \\
\midrule
T-A & \xmark\,\xmark\,\xmark & \xmark\,\xmark\,\xmark & \cmark\;r1 \\
T-B & \xmark\,\xmark\,\xmark & \xmark\,\xmark\,\xmark & \xmark\,\xmark\,\xmark \\
T-C & \xmark\,\xmark\,\xmark & \xmark\,\xmark\,\xmark & \cmark\;r1 \\
\midrule
Useful / 3 & 0 / 3 & 0 / 3 & \textbf{2 / 3} \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

The headline finding is that PosOnly equals NoKB on these
research sub-questions: a successes-only bank does not move the
team off the no-bank baseline within three rounds. Only the full
$\text{positive}+\text{negative}$ bank produces a step change of
$+67$ percentage points, and PosNeg achieves it at the first
round on both solvable cells. The asymmetry between PosOnly and
PosNeg is therefore not a size-of-bank effect but a
kind-of-knowledge effect: warnings against \emph{transferring} a
known-working method to a regime where it fails cannot be
reconstructed from positive entries alone.

\paragraph{Mechanism: method choice on T-C.} The bore-soliton
sub-question exposes how negative entries reshape method
selection. \Cref{tab:bkdv-tc-method} shows what each condition
chose at round~1.

\begin{table}[tb]
\centering
\caption{Round-1 numerical scheme each condition chose for T-C
(Burgers bore on $u$ coupled to a KdV soliton on $v$).}
\label{tab:bkdv-tc-method}
\begin{tabular}{l p{0.50\columnwidth} c}
\toprule
Cond.\ & Scheme & Outcome \\
\midrule
NoKB    & spectral $+$ explicit RK4 on both fields & NaN \\
PosOnly & Fourier IMEX-CN spectral on both fields  & NaN \\
PosNeg  & MUSCL$+$Godunov FV on $u$, IMEX-CN spectral on $v$ &
\textbf{useful} \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

NoKB selects the textbook KdV default---pseudo-spectral with
explicit RK4---which the bank already records as failing under
stiff dispersion and shock formation, but NoKB cannot see those
records. PosOnly selects the positively-recorded method
(IMEX-CN spectral) and applies it uniformly; the positive bank
says what worked on KdV but contains no entry warning that the
same method fails on a sharp Burgers bore. PosNeg's
\texttt{reasoning.md} cites four distinct negative entries---
central-FD Gibbs on Burgers, central-FD positivity loss on
shallow water, the cross-domain ``central FD on hyperbolic''
synthesis, and the explicit-RK4 stiffness blow-up on KdV---to
\emph{justify why not} to use any single uniform scheme, and
splits the methods by component. PosOnly only converges on the
split scheme by round~3, with a time step that still lets the
bore blow up.

\paragraph{T-B as an honest negative finding.} All three
conditions fail T-B. The Gaussian-to-soliton-train decomposition
needs several requirements jointly (sufficient $T$, full
dealiasing, careful time step at amplitude $4$) that no single
bank entry covers. The most relevant entry,
\texttt{kb-gardner-nonlinearCFL-amplitude-boundary}, records a
\emph{qualitative} warning---``$dt \cdot (6A + 1.5A^2) \cdot
k_{\max} < O(1)$''---without a usable numeric threshold. PosNeg
attempts smaller time steps in rounds~2 and~3 but blows up by
several orders of magnitude. The case study therefore exposes a
gap: the schema supports \emph{categorical} guidance well but
needs richer \emph{quantitative-bound} fields to cover edge-of-CFL
regimes. We treat T-B's failure as informative rather than
suppressing it, and return to the schema gap in
\cref{sec:limitations}.

\paragraph{Token economy and citation pattern.}
On the two cells PosNeg solves, it spends $32$k and $33$k tokens
(round~1 only) versus $55$--$67$k for NoKB and PosOnly across
three rounds---roughly $40$--$50\%$ fewer tokens because early
PASS skips rounds 2 and 3. A simple grep of \texttt{reasoning.md}
files shows PosNeg agents cite about three times as many bank
entries as PosOnly agents on the solvable cells (e.g., $\sim$9
vs $\sim$3 on T-C), with at least four of the PosNeg citations
in each cell being \emph{negative} entries used to argue against
a candidate method.

\paragraph{Feasibility seeds.} Two prior pilots provided
existence proofs before Stage~2 was launched: a Burgers shock
solved by a TVD scheme ($L^1{=}0.0029$), and a KdV soliton that
initially returned 256 NaNs and then converged after a single
negative record switched the time-integration route from
integrating-factor RK4 to IMEX-spectral (peak $x{=}3.05$,
amplitude $2.03$, mass $4.000$). These pilots motivated the
forced-basic-method design of Stage~1 and are reflected as
seed entries in the bank.

