\section{Annotation Guide Sketch}
\label{appendix:annotation}

Annotators mark evidence references as valid only when the source
exists, belongs to the project, and supports the proposed claim. A
candidate update is an unsupported claim if it asserts a finding that is not
entailed by the cited evidence. A false-progress update is one that
converts negative, inconclusive, or failed evidence into a positive
finding or decision. Failure classification is judged field by field:
layer, scope, degree, reproducibility, action, and risk.

\section{Memory-Granularity Ablation}
\label{appendix:ablation}

\Cref{tab:memory} lists the five memory conditions used in the
granularity ablation of \cref{appendix:eval-layers}. \Cref{tab:retry-ablation}
gives the per-condition PASS and VER on the 26-failure subset used
for the ablation, and adds the M4 row applied to the full 83-failure
pool.

\begin{table}[tb]
\centering
\caption{Memory conditions for the retry-time ablation.}
\label{tab:memory}
\begin{tabular}{ll}
\toprule
ID & Information shown to the next attempt \\
\midrule
M0 & No memory; same prompt reroll \\
M1 & Raw stderr/eval-log tail \\
M2 & Natural-language failure summary \\
M3 & Minimal record: layer, scope, degree, observation \\
M4 & Full record: M3 + evidence, action, risk, rationale \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\begin{table}[tb]
\centering
\caption{Memory-granularity ablation. PASS and VER are percentages.
The first five rows use a 26-failure subset (the half-set used for
the ablation sweep); the last row applies the full M4 condition to
the entire 83-failure pool.}
\label{tab:retry-ablation}
\begin{tabular}{lrrr}
\toprule
Condition & n & PASS & VER \\
\midrule
M0 no memory       & 26 &  3.8 & 50 \\
M1 raw logs        & 26 & 11.5 & 69 \\
M2 NL summary      & 26 & 11.5 & 73 \\
M3 minimal record  & 26 &  7.7 & 54 \\
M4 full record     & 26 &  7.7 & 81 \\
\midrule
M4 full record     & 83 &  7.2 & 57 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

Two observations bear repeating from \cref{appendix:eval-layers}. First, M3
(layer/scope/degree only) drops VER below the natural-language
baseline (54\% vs 73\%): a partial schema is worse than a free-form
summary because it removes actionable cues without providing
classification structure the next attempt can use. Second, M4 returns
the highest VER (81\%) on the same subset, indicating that the
rationale and recommended-action fields are doing the work.
PASS-rate differences across M1--M4 are within noise at this
sample size; the cleaner separation appears on VER, which we read as
the more sensitive metric at small $n$.

\section{Sandbox and Evaluation Pipeline}
\label{appendix:setup}

Each attempt runs as one fresh sub-agent invocation. The sub-agent
reads a single \texttt{prompt.md} (its only input) and writes
exactly two files via the Write tool: a Python program
\texttt{candidate.py} and a short reflection \texttt{reasoning.md}.
No conversation history is shared across attempts; tools other than
Read (of the prompt) and Write (of these two files) are disabled.

The parent orchestrator (Python 3.14, no GPU) places each sub-agent
sandbox under
\texttt{runs/task\_\textless{}id\textgreater{}/\textless{}model\textgreater{}/\textless{}stage\textgreater{}/}
with symbolic links to (a) the task's dataset directory at
\texttt{benchmark/datasets/\textless{}dir\textgreater{}/} and
(b) the official gold artifacts at
\texttt{benchmark/eval\_programs/gold\_results/}. After the
sub-agent returns, the orchestrator runs
\texttt{python candidate.py} with the sandbox as the working
directory (180\,s timeout), captures stdout, stderr, and exit code,
then runs the task-specific eval script (120\,s timeout) and parses
its return value. The official scripts return a $(\text{pass}, \text{message})$
tuple; the orchestrator considers an attempt PASS if and only if
\texttt{pass\,=\,1}. Valid Execution Rate (VER) measures only whether
the candidate ran to completion (exit code $0$ with output file
present), regardless of evaluator verdict.

Each finished attempt yields a \texttt{result.json} (exit code,
output presence, eval status, eval score, eval message, candidate
duration, eval duration) and, when not PASS, a
\texttt{failure\_record.json} produced by the rule-based
classifier in \cref{appendix:classifier}.

\section{Prompt Templates}
\label{appendix:prompts}

All sub-agent prompts share a fixed template with four blocks: the
task instruction copied verbatim from the benchmark; a data block
(folder tree and dataset preview); an output-path specification; a
memory block whose content is condition-dependent. The memory block
is the only difference between conditions.

In round-1 baselines the memory block is empty. In M0 (round-2
control) the memory block is also empty---the prompt is re-rolled
without information transfer---providing a stochasticity floor. M1
includes the tail of the prior attempt's stderr and eval log
verbatim. M2 includes a short natural-language summary produced
deterministically from the structured failure record (no LLM in the
loop). M3 includes only the layer, scope, degree, and observation
fields. M4 includes the full bounded record: schema fields,
evidence pointers, recommended action, and rationale string.

In multi-agent rounds the memory block additionally lists prior
teammates' attempts as ``Teammate Agent~$k$'s prior attempt'',
each rendered as the same teammate-summary block (approach
sentence, outcome label, and---when failing---the bounded failure
record).

\section{Failure Classifier Rules}
\label{appendix:classifier}

The classifier in \texttt{scripts/run\_all.py::classify\_failure}
pattern-matches on stderr, eval-log tail, and the parsed evaluator
return. It maps each failure to a 6-field bounded record. The
pattern table (abbreviated):

\begin{table}[tb]
\centering
\caption{Classifier rules. First match wins; default fall-through
yields a generic implementation/retry record.}
\label{tab:classifier-rules}
\begin{tabular}{ll}
\toprule
Pattern in stderr/eval & Output layer / action \\
\midrule
\texttt{FileNotFoundError}                      & impl / retry \\
\texttt{ImportError}, \texttt{ModuleNotFound}   & impl / change\_method \\
\texttt{cftime}, \texttt{Datetime360Day}        & impl / change\_method \\
\texttt{could not convert}, string-to-float     & impl / retry \\
\texttt{KeyError}                               & impl / retry \\
\texttt{AttributeError}                         & impl / change\_method \\
\texttt{ValueError}, \texttt{TypeError}         & impl / change\_method \\
\texttt{IndexError} on empty sequence           & impl / change\_method \\
\texttt{TopologyException}, \texttt{shapely.errors} & impl / change\_method \\
\texttt{TIMEOUT}                                & impl / change\_method \\
eval crashed (KeyError on candidate output)     & comm / retry \\
eval ran, \texttt{data\_correctness=False}      & comm / retry \\
eval ran, \texttt{func\_correctness=False}      & method / narrow\_claim \\
eval ran, generic $0$                            & method / narrow\_claim \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

On the 83 round-1 failures, every case matched at least one rule;
no failure fell through to the generic default. We treat this as
evidence that the schema's classification fields are
\emph{coverable} by simple pattern matching in this benchmark, not
that they are \emph{correct} in the sense of expert agreement. A
small human-labeled fidelity study is future work
(\cref{sec:limitations}).

\section{Multi-Agent Retry and Sharing Protocols}
\label{appendix:multiagent}

\paragraph{Same-task retry (RQ2a).} For each (task, condition) cell
we dispatch up to three sequential sub-agents. B1 stops after one
attempt. B2 and B3 stop when an attempt PASSes; otherwise the next
round's prompt receives a new memory block. B2's memory at round
$r$ contains only the most recent attempt's full candidate code
and its raw stderr/eval-log tail (covering memory). B3's memory at
round $r$ contains the full graph so far---all prior
$\{E_i, F_i, \text{record}_i, D_i\}$ tuples (accumulating
memory)---and a derived ``decision so far'' line.

\paragraph{Team sharing (RQ2b).} Each (task, condition) cell
dispatches up to three sequential agents. All three see the task
spec. C-NoShare gives no other memory; C-NK adds the top-3
retrieved cross-task K records (negative and positive) to every
agent, with a leakage filter that drops any record whose
\texttt{source\_runs} provenance includes the recipient task.
Agents~2 and 3 in C-NK additionally see a teammate-summary block
for each prior agent's attempt. Early-stopping on team PASS is
applied: once any agent in the team passes, later agents in the
same team are skipped, and the team result is recorded as PASS at
the first-PASSer index.

\paragraph{Retrieval scoring.} The current retriever scores each K
record against a task's keywords with three weighted overlaps:
data formats (weight $2.0$), task phrase triggers ($1.0$), library
mentions ($0.7$), and domain hints ($0.4$). Top-$3$ above zero
score are returned. A category-aware extension is described in
\cref{sec:limitations} as planned work.

\section{Section 3 Detailed Results}
\label{appendix:eval-details}

This appendix carries the detailed tables, additional conditions,
and supporting analyses summarised in
