\subsection{Per-layer breakdown}
\label{appendix:eval-layers}

The r1 curator self-labels each NK with a \texttt{failure.layer}
value. On the 24 NK-test tasks the distribution is $15$
implementation, $7$ communication, $2$ method.

\begin{table}[tb]
\centering
\caption{PASS by initial failure layer on the NK-test subset
($n = 24$). Communication failures are most repairable across all
memory regimes; method failures are unrepairable at this sample
size. This pattern reproduces the order-of-magnitude separation
reported in an earlier version of this paper on $n = 83$ failures
across three models, the data behind the granularity ablation in
\cref{appendix:ablation}.}
\label{tab:appendix-per-layer}
\begin{tabular}{lrrrr}
\toprule
Failure layer & $n$ & NKR any-round & B2 covering & deepNKR Sonnet \\
\midrule
Communication      & 7  & 2\,/\,7 (29\%)  & 2\,/\,7 (29\%)  & 0\,/\,7 \\
Implementation     & 15 & 1\,/\,15 (7\%)  & 3\,/\,15 (20\%) & 1\,/\,15 (7\%) \\
Method             & 2  & 0\,/\,2         & 0\,/\,2         & 0\,/\,2 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

The communication-layer PASS rate is consistently the highest
across memory regimes: schema, key, or column-name mismatches are
both easy to flag in NK and easy to act on. The implementation
layer's higher B2 rate ($20\%$) than NKR rate ($7\%$) reflects
that some implementation defects (multiprocessing forks, dtype
overflow) need the raw \texttt{exec.log} traceback to localise,
which covering memory carries but a compressed NK strips.

\subsection{NK error rate (r2-curator self-report)}
\label{appendix:eval-errors}

The r2 curator's \texttt{relationship\_to\_round1} field gives a
structured self-reported error rate for depth-1 NKs:

\begin{table}[tb]
\centering
\caption{r2-curator self-reported assessment of the depth-1 r1 NK
on the 22 tasks that proceeded to round 3.}
\label{tab:appendix-nk-errors}
\begin{tabular}{lrr}
\toprule
relationship\_to\_round1 & $n$ & \% \\
\midrule
\texttt{round1\_recipe\_was\_correct\_but\_insufficient} & 13 & 59 \\
\texttt{new\_failure\_mode\_unrelated\_to\_round1}        & 7  & 32 \\
\texttt{round1\_recipe\_was\_wrong}                       & 2  & 9 \\
\texttt{round1\_recipe\_was\_misapplied}                  & 0  & 0 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

Both \texttt{round1\_recipe\_was\_wrong} verdicts are valid on
manual inspection. Task 029's depth-1 NK proposed swapping the
non-existent dict key \texttt{eda\_signals['EDA\_SCR\_Peaks']}
for \texttt{eda\_info['EDA\_Peaks']}, but that key is also
absent; task 067's depth-1 NK recommended flattening two vectors
to a common dimension for cosine, which numerically succeeds but
is semantically meaningless (W's rows are JNMF latent factors,
not vocabulary tokens). Depth-1 NK therefore has a measured $9\%$
error rate on this subset; the $0\%$
\texttt{round1\_recipe\_was\_misapplied} rate means downstream
agents do not have trouble \emph{following} depth-1 advice, only
\emph{relying on} it when it is wrong. This quantifies one
benefit of the depth axis: a depth-3 NK draws on three rounds of
failure evidence, reducing the fraction of NKs that confidently
identify a wrong fix.

\subsection{Cross-model transfer: Haiku 4.5 on the depth-3 NK}
\label{appendix:eval-cross-model}

We tested whether the depth-3 NK produced by a Sonnet curator from
Sonnet's three-round failure trajectory transfers to a different
solver model. We chose Haiku~4.5 --- strictly weaker than
Sonnet~4.6 --- so the question is sharp: can rich NK compensate
for solver weakness?

\textbf{Result.} Haiku PASSes $0/19$ on the hard subset.
Distribution: $13$ \texttt{exec\_fail}, $3$ \texttt{eval\_fail},
$2$ \texttt{eval\_crash}, $1$ no-output.

\textbf{Inspection.} The failure mode is not ``NK gave bad
advice''. Spot-checks: on task 034 (NeuroKit2 + NumPy~2.0
incompatibility), the depth-3 NK's recommended fix was correct,
but Haiku introduced a NumPy shape error (\texttt{ValueError:
diff requires input that is at least one dimensional}) in its
implementation; on task 002, Haiku hallucinated a non-existent
module path (\texttt{from matminer.features import \ldots}; the
actual module is \texttt{matminer.featurizers}).

\textbf{Reading.} NK transfers the \emph{conceptual} layer of a
solution (diagnosis, ruled-out routes, recommended approach), but
does not substitute for solver-model implementation reliability.
A weak downstream solver cannot fully cash in on a rich NK. The
cleaner future experiment is ``does depth-3 NK help a
\emph{comparable}-strength model that has not seen this
exploration''; that requires a second Sonnet-class model not
yet available.

\subsection{Solver tokens and end-to-end pipeline cost}
\label{appendix:eval-tokens}

\begin{table}[tb]
\centering
\caption{Solver tokens per dispatch (median; $n$ as reported).
NK conditions cost $11$--$18\%$ more tokens per dispatch than
the no-memory baseline; covering memory costs $21\%$ more; the
Haiku cross-model condition spends $2.5\times$ Sonnet's tokens
on the same depth-3 NK.}
\label{tab:appendix-tokens}
\begin{tabular}{lrrr}
\toprule
Cell & $n$ & median tokens & $\Delta$ vs round-1 \\
\midrule
Round-1 (no memory)              & 24 & 16\,262 & --- \\
Round-2 B0 (retry)               & 24 & 16\,391 & $+1\%$ \\
Round-2 NKR (depth-1)            & 24 & 18\,081 & $+11\%$ \\
Round-2 B2 (covering)            & 24 & 19\,642 & $+21\%$ \\
deepNKR Sonnet (depth-3)         & 19 & 19\,247 & $+18\%$ \\
deepNKR Haiku (cross-model)      & 19 & 48\,360 & $+197\%$ \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\paragraph{Curator tokens.} The depth-1 r1 curator costs a
median of $\approx 19$\,K tokens per dispatch; the depth-1 r2
curator costs $\approx 20$\,K; the depth-3 curator costs
$\approx 27$\,K. Depth increases curator cost roughly linearly
in evidence-rounds.

\paragraph{End-to-end per-task cost (curator + 2 solver rounds).}
The depth-1 NK pipeline costs $\approx 76$\,K tokens
($19+20$\,K curator $+$ $18+19$\,K solver across two rounds)
versus $\approx 40$\,K for B2 covering memory (no curator).
The depth-3 NK pipeline, single replay, costs $\approx 46$\,K
($27$\,K deep curator $+$ $19$\,K solver). \textbf{Per single
replay, NK is more expensive than covering memory} because
curator tokens are paid upfront. NK's economic advantage
materialises only under amortisation --- the same NK consulted
by multiple downstream agents or related tasks. The break-even
point for depth-1 NK against B2 is approximately $10$ replays.
\Cref{sec:case-study} tests the amortised regime directly.

\subsection{Curator audit-trail schema}
\label{appendix:eval-audit}

Every NK record has a paired audit record at
\path{section3/04_outputs/curator_audit/task_<id>{,_r2,_deep}.json}.
The schema captures:
\begin{itemize}
\item the prompt the curator received (full text, sha256, byte
  count);
\item every input file the curator was allowed to read (full
  content + sha256 + byte count); for depth-3 curators this
  includes all 12 round-1/2/3 artifacts;
\item the NK record the curator wrote (full content, sha256,
  byte count, parse status);
\item runtime metadata: \texttt{agent\_id, return\_message,
  total\_tokens, tool\_uses, duration\_ms}, UTC dispatch and
  completion timestamps.
\end{itemize}
Across $65$ curator invocations ($24$ depth-1 r1, $22$ depth-1
r2, $19$ depth-3 deep), every NK parses as JSON, no curator read
a file outside its allowlist, and every audit record is
self-contained.

